Travellers no longer need to show a negative PCR test to gain entry to South Africa. The Tourism Business Council of SA's Tshifhiwa Tshivhengwa says allowing fully vaccinated people into the country without requiring a test as well will help the tourism sector's recovery. #eNCA Courtesy #DStv403  JOHANNESBURG - The Tourism Business Council of South Africa's Tshifhiwa Tshivhengwa says allowing fully vaccinated people into the country without requiring a test will help the tourism sector's recovery. READ: Masks no longer required when outdoors in SA He says PCR tests are expensive and make it difficult to travel. Announcing eased COVID-19 regulations on Tuesday, President Cyril Ramaphosa said visitors need to show only proof of vaccination. However, those who are not vaccinated will need to get to a negative PCR test, not older than 72 hours.   There's been a steady decline in the number of coronavirus cases countrywide over the past few weeks.